{{Other uses|April Showers (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Snow shower on Dartmoor.jpg|thumb|right|An approaching April shower of snow on [[Dartmoor]], [[Devon]], England. (31 March 2010)]]
In the United Kingdom and Ireland, an '''April shower''' is [[rain]] during the month of April. One of the major causes of the often heavy downpours is the position of the [[jet stream]].<ref name="bbc">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/features/understanding/april_showers.shtml |year=2008 |publisher=BBC Weather centre |accessdate=2008-06-25 |title=April Showers|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125044045/http://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/features/understanding/april_showers.shtml|archivedate=2009-01-25}}</ref> In early spring, the jet stream starts to move northwards, allowing large depressions to bring strong winds and rain in from the Atlantic. In one day the weather can change from springtime sunshine to winter sleet and snow. The track of these depressions can often be across Ireland and Scotland bringing bands of rain followed by heavy showers (often of hail or snow) and strong blustery winds.

The [[proverb]] "March winds and April showers bring forth May flowers", first recorded in 1886,<ref>{{cite book
|last=Apperson|first=George Latimer|last2=Manser|first2=Martin H
|title=Dictionary of Proverbs|publisher=[[Wordsworth Editions]]|page=372
|isbn=1-84022-311-1|year=2006|accessdate=2013-02-23
|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=7PMZJqSR4sAC&pg=PA372#v=onepage&q&f=false
}}</ref> or the shorter, [[trochaic]] version "April showers bring May flowers" (originally "Sweet April showers/Do spring May flowers", part of a poem recorded in 1610<ref>Northall, G. F. ''English Folk-Rhymes: A collection of traditional verses relating to places and persons, customs, superstitions, etc.'' 1892. pg. 430</ref>) are common expressions in English speaking countries. The phrase is referenced in the [[General Prologue]] of [[The Canterbury Tales]]: 
"Whan that Aprill, with his shoures soote 
The droghte of March hath perced to the roote".<ref name="Librarius">{{cite web|title = The Canterbury Tales: General Prologue |url=http://www.librarius.com/cantales/genpro.htm |year=2017 |publisher=Librarius |accessdate=2017-02-27}}</ref>

