{{Politics of the Cayman Islands}}
'''General elections''' were held in the [[Cayman Islands]] in November 1984.<ref name=LC>[http://countrystudies.us/caribbean-islands/131.htm Government and Politics] [[Library of Congress Country Studies]]</ref> The ruling [[Unity Team]] led by [[Jim Bodden]] lost all eight seats due to a scandal over Caymanian banks being used to launder drug money.<ref name=LC/> The opposition [[Dignity Team]] of [[Benson Ebanks]] won three seats in the [[Legislative Assembly of the Cayman Islands|Legislative Assembly]], but the majority (nine) were won by independents.<ref name=CA>Charles D. Ameringer (1992) ''Political Parties of the Americas, 1980s to 1990s: Canada, Latin America, and the West Indies'', Greenwood Publishing Group, p168</ref> Ebanks subsequently became Chief Minister after forming a coalition.<ref name=CA/>
